<p class="p">Wetting behaviors on solid surface is mostly reflected by measuring the water contact angle (WCA) [
 <xref rid="B71-polymers-11-00806" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">71</xref>]. For an ideal smooth surface, WCA refers to the results of interactions between gas, liquid, and solid phases (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="polymers-11-00806-f004" class="xref">Figure 4</xref>). Usually, the WCA can be obtained by Young’s equation [
 <xref rid="B72-polymers-11-00806" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">72</xref>]: 
 <disp-formula id="FD1-polymers-11-00806" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(1)</label>
  <math id="mm1" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi class="mi">cos</mi>
     <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mfrac class="mfrac">
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mi class="mi">gs</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
       <mo class="mo">−</mo>
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mi class="mi">sl</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
      <mrow class="mrow">
       <msub class="msub">
        <mi class="mi">γ</mi>
        <mrow class="mrow">
         <mi class="mi">gl</mi>
        </mrow>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic> represents the intrinsic contact angle, and 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">gs</sub>, 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">sl</sub>, 
 <italic class="italic">γ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">gl</sub> are the surface energy of gas-solid, solid-liquid, and gas-liquid interfaces, respectively. When 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic> &lt; 90°, the surface is hydrophilic (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="polymers-11-00806-f004" class="xref">Figure 4</xref>) while the surface is hydrophobic when 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic> &gt; 90° (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="polymers-11-00806-f004" class="xref">Figure 4</xref>). 
</p>
